> It's great that you are taking an interest in Ben's health and education
> at this point. Heather will be able to tell you about the challenges Ben
> faced in the classroom, Dr. Cebulski can help you to understand the
> testing process and the report, and Dr. Fraser will be able to dispel
> myths about adderall. Together, they can explain why this is not a case
> of growing pains, that medication is safe and effective, and that it is
> important to begin treatment.
> 
> Heather can be reached through the school (call to make an appointment)
> Dr. Cebulski's contact information is on the report Dr. Fraser's office:
> 613.680.1065
> 
> We may all have different opinions about this, but we have an obligation
> to act in Ben's best interest, regardless of our own personal feelings.
> The most reasonable way to do this is to make a decision based on
> professional opinion and evidence. We are aware of the benefits and
> risks of medication, but we are also aware of the risks of not treating
> ADHD. Behavioural treatment alone doesn't work as well, takes longer,
> and is more challenging to implement. If effective, the medication will
> help Ben function better, and make behavioral treatment easier for him.
> According to Heather, Dr. Cebulski and Ben, Ben is facing functional
> attention deficits that are impacting his learning, progress and
> self-esteem. Dr. Fraser prescribed the medication based on all of the
> information provided, and the standard of care for childhood ADHD. At
> this point, based on all of the available evidence, we're convinced that
> it is in Ben's best interest to start medication.
> 
> To make an informed decision, it's necessary to understand what the
> drugs do, how they help, and what the side effects are. Here is more
> information about treatment:
> - http://www.caddra.ca/cms4/pdfs/caddraGuidelines2011.pdf
> - http://help4adhd.org/en/treatment/medication/WWK3
> - http://www.cdc.gov/ncbddd/adhd/guidelines.html
> - Here is the link to the health canada report, published in August,
> 2005, that found no link between adderall and cardiac arrest. The
> temporary suspension was lifted following the findings of the committee.
> http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/dhp-mps/alt_formats/hpfb-dgpsa/pdf/prodpharma/ndc
> a_rep_cnma_rap_2005-08-25-eng.pdf
> 
> CMH
